g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Visitor pattern violates the Single Responsibility Princi...

g.text: The Visitor pattern violates the Single Responsibility Principle by possibly breaking encapsulation of the Elements and decreasing its readability. Encapsulation, the Visitors might require information from the Elements that is not exposed by default. The Visitors need this information to perform there algorithmic logic correctly. As a consequence, Elements might need to expose more information on their interface to satisfy the Visitor’s needs. This violates encapsulation. The alternative, to situate the Visitor logic directly inside the Elements hierarchy, would not require breaking this encapsulation. However, this might endanger the stability of Elements hierarchy. The consequence of violating encapsulation is unwanted coupling, that might impact the adaptability to change the system later. Readability, the logic of each concrete Element is scattered across a Visitor and the Element itself. This might cause a decrease in readability, because the logic is scattered. However, as mentioned in the ‘why?’ section it might also cause a increase in readability. The readability ‘gain’ of the Visitor pattern is achieved in case we are interested in all concrete implementations of a specific algorithm (=Visitor). The pattern introduces a readability ‘loss’ in case we are interested in each individual concrete implementation.

g.title: Folded Corner.276
g.desc: The Visitor pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by ...

g.text: The Visitor pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by enabling introduction of new Algorithms (= Visitors) without modification of an existing class hierarchy (= Elements). This provides stability and improves maintainability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where we would situated the algorithmic logic (=Visitors) directly into an existing class hierarchy (=Elements). Stability, because the Element hierarchy remains untouched when new functionality (related to this hierarchy) is introduced. This ensures stability in both the clients of the Element hierarchy as the Elements them-self. The Elements do not require change to support new logic. This mitigates the risk of breaking stable, existing Element code. The clients of the Elements do not have to be recompiled, redeployed or change in their test code, because the interface of the Elements hierarchy does not change. Maintainability, because the double dispatch mechanism, used by the Visitor pattern, might reduce the cyclomatic complexity of the code. Reduction of the cyclomatic complexity of the code is achieved by decomposition of conditional structures. Those conditional structures are committed to type checking to execute the appropriate behavior. Double dispatch ‘shifts’ this responsibility from caller to callee. The callee calls its appropriate behavior on the respective caller. Reduction in the cyclomatic complexity of the code results in code that we can easier understand, change or extend. These aspects contribute to the maintainability aspect of the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Visitor pattern enables stability in an existing code bas...

g.text: The Visitor pattern enables stability in an existing code base. A common scenario: an existing class hierarchy (=Elements), intertwined in our code base, requires change in its interface. Changing the Elements might endanger malfunction in already working code. Also, clients of these Elements need to recompile, redeploy and change test code (mocks). The Visitor pattern prescribes ‘extracting’ newly introduced logic into a separate class, called a Visitor. A Visitor contains the algorithmic behavior for each concrete Element. This means a single Visitor defines a ‘Visit’ function that corresponds to each concrete Element. The Element hierarchy requires an one time change, namely an ‘Accept’ function that accepts the Visitor. A new algorithm, applicable to the object structure, can now be introduced with relative ease; extend the Visitor interface with a new concrete Visitor and pass it to the respective Elements. The power of the pattern manifest itself when we expect introduction of multiple algorithms on an existing object structure.

g.title: Folded Corner.303
g.desc: The Visitor pattern uses double dispatch to realize stability...

g.text: The Visitor pattern uses double dispatch to realize stability on an existing object structure. Double dispatch enables decomposition of conditional structures and resolves possible language constraints. We often collide with decision logic, based on enums or casting, to execute the correct behavior based on the respective type. This might result in ‘extensive’ conditional statements, which in essence represents a v-table. The Visitor pattern might resolve this Cyclomatic complexity. Example: a caller contains a list of callees that follow a (common) base class. The caller iterates over them, checks their type, and executes the corresponding behavior. The caller needs to check the type, while the callee already knows its type. The Visitor pattern prescribes us to apply an ‘Accept’ functionality in the callee and a ‘Visit’ functionality in the caller. The caller will pass itself to the callee, the callee will dispatch the appropriate caller and passes itself as an argument. Using abstractions for both caller and callee will make this solution double dispatch. Using this approach will reduce the cyclomatic complexity of our code and provide a more robust alternative. The same approach can be used for sorting a list of base class elements. The Visitor pattern could also help in resolving language dependent constraints. For example the problem of overloading in C++ . Overloading is a static form of Polymorphism, which ‘malfunctions’ when working with runtime Polymorphic types.

g.title: Folded Corner.313
g.desc: The Visitor pattern enables separation of concern by separati...

g.text: The Visitor pattern enables separation of concern by separating ‘unrelated’ algorithms (=Visitors) from a class hierarchy (=Elements). The problem might arise where is it required to execute an algorithm on an (existing) object structure, but it feels ‘unnatural’ to fit in the interface of the object structure or client. The Visitor pattern prescribes to localize this algorithmic behavior into a separate class. The result is that both client and Elements are simplified. The Elements core logic is not obscured by algorithmic logic that might ‘distract’ from its essence. Vice-versa is true as well, the algorithms are not obscured by logic from the Elements. The variants of an algorithm are not scattered across concrete Elements, but instead situated in a single Visitor.

g.title: Folded Corner.316
g.desc: The Visitor pattern enables the possibility to apply algorith...

g.text: The Visitor pattern enables the possibility to apply algorithmic logic across different types of classes (i.e. classes that do not have a common base class). The Visitor pattern requires a mechanism to ‘Visit’ each Element in an object structure. An implementation problem, with respect to iteration, might arise when the Elements (in an object structure) do not have a common base class. This problem might be resolved via language specifics. In C++ it is possible to resolve this problem by using std::variant in combination with std::visit.

g.title: Folded Corner.330
g.desc: The Visitor pattern compliments the Single Responsibility pri...

g.text: The Visitor pattern compliments the Single Responsibility principle by centralizing unrelated logic from a class hierarchy (=Elements) into its own class hierarchy (=Visitors). This provides readability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where we would situated ‘unrelated’ algorithmic logic (=Visitors) directly into an existing class hierarchy (=Elements). Readability, because functionality that would otherwise obscure the core logic of the Elements is now extracted in a Visitor class. This means the Elements re-main ‘focused’ and readable. Additionally, a Visitor contains all the different variants of an algorithm. This means the logic is not scattered across the Element’s sub classes, but localized into a single place (Visitor). This might result in enhanced readability, because the different variants of an algorithm can be viewed in a single ‘glance’.

g.title: Folded Corner.336
g.desc: The Visitors in the Visitor pattern follow a common interface...

g.text: The Visitors in the Visitor pattern follow a common interface. Not all Visitors may apply to every Element in the object structure. This enforces newly introduced Visitors to implement ‘Visit’ functions they do not need. This violates the Interface Segregation principle. Implementing empty ‘Visit’ functions introduces redundant code and additional maintenance (e.g. the signature of a function changes).

g.title: Folded Corner.341
g.desc: The Visitor pattern allows introduction of new functionality ...

g.text: The Visitor pattern allows introduction of new functionality (=Visitors) on an existing class hierarchy (=Elements). The Visitors contain a ‘Visit’ function for each concrete class of the Element hierarchy. The Elements contain a single ‘Accept’ function that accepts an abstract Visitor. Changing the Visitor, that operates on Elements hierarchy, requires a new concrete Visitor. Introducing a new Element requires, besides introduction of a new class, all the Visitors to change. This is because the Visitors should support this new Element which requires the Visitor’s interface to change. A general rule for the applicability of the Visitor pattern is to use it when the algorithm applied over an object structure changes more frequently then the Elements themselves. Otherwise the pattern might negatively impact the maintainability aspect of the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.344
g.desc: The Visitor pattern both entails the negative and positive as...

g.text: The Visitor pattern both entails the negative and positive aspects of the Open Closed Principle. The Visitor pattern introduces an additional form of indirection via its Visitor(s). In contrast, situating the Visitor logic directly inside the Elements would overcome this form of indirection. Indirection reduces the debuggability and navigability of the code. Another aspect is the double dispatching. This might complicate the code, because it might be unexpected and confusing that communication is bidirectional in a single function call.
